This paper discusses the implementation of open-endedness in evolutionary systems, which is a topic that falls under the subfield of artificial intelligence and machine learning. Specifically, the paper focuses on the formalism and processes required for an evolutionary process, which is related to the subfield of neural networks (cs.NE). The paper also discusses the interactions between these processes and their modes of implementation, which is related to the subfield of robotics (cs.RO) and systems and control (cs.SY). Additionally, the paper discusses the categorization and comparison of open-ended evolutionary potential, which is related to the subfield of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
